commit.message:
fix(policy): allow forward ports w/ to-addr for egress-zone=HOST

If the destination address is the host then this is necessary. A policy
with egress-zone=ANY does not work because the policy dispatch will
match the egress zones "source" in the destination address.

feat: add a service for MNPD protocol

It's used by winbox to find devices over network using MNPD or CDP
protocol.

Signed-off-by: Mariusz Fik <mariusz@fidano.pl>

feat(service): add WS-Discovery host

Add a generic service definition for a WS-Discovery host implementation,
which, e.g., allows to discover Samba file sharing services via Windows.
As per https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/win32/wsdapi/additional-ws-discovery-functionality,
TCP port 5357 is used by the service and respective implementations (see
below).

The file re-uses the already existing UDP multicast service definition.

The service file is taken from openSUSE (see
https://build.opensuse.org/package/view_file/openSUSE:Leap:15.5/wsdd/wsdd.xml),
which did not validate against the firewalld serivce schema. Thus, the
include statement was moved. The original author of the openSUSE
package, suggested to upstream a generic service definition that is
agnostic to a specific implementation, like wsdd
(https://github.com/christgau/wsdd) or wsdd2
(https://github.com/Netgear/wsdd2).

See also: https://github.com/christgau/wsdd/pull/186

Co-authored-by: Herbert Graeber <herbert@graeber-clan.de>

improvement(fw-in-container): support (re)setting size with "--setup-host"

By default, the "--setup-host" bumps the sysctls to 4000k, which should
allow our tests to pass inside fw-in-container.

  $ sudo ./contrib/fw-in-container/fw-in-container -S

Now, also accept an optional size argument to "-S". With this,

  $ sudo ./contrib/fw-in-container/fw-in-container -S $((8000*1024))

explicitly selects the requested size.

The main use is however

  $ sudo ./contrib/fw-in-container/fw-in-container 0

to reset the value sysctl. In this case, "0" is an alias for "212992",
which is the default on my Fedora machine. The point is to be able to
reset the default.

The skip was not properly detected due to a bug. Fix it.

improvement(fw_transaction): use context manager for temporary transactions

Instead of repeating this code over and over, add a context manager
which will automatically execute the create transaction at exit.

Maybe a better question would be, why all those lower-level functions
like FirewallZone.create_zone_base_by_chain() needs to handle being
called without a transaction and create a new (short lived) transaction.
It seems most of those function should require the caller to pass a
transaction along.

Anyway, this patch doesn't address that. Instead it drops a large
amount of redundant code.

improvement(fw_transaction): do nothing in transaction.execute() for empty transaction

We will add a context manager, which always execute() the transaction
at the end.

If the transaction was already executed (and cleared) before, or if
the transaction is still empty, don't do anything.

This mainly only supresses the logging about executing the transaction.

improvement(fw_transaction): automatically clear the transaction after execute

It's unlikely that it makes sense to run the same commands again, after
executing the transaction.

In fact, all callers either directly call clear() after execute(). Or
they call execute() on a transaction they created themselves (and which
isn't used afterwards).

Automatically call clear(). The caller could still opt-out from it.

improvement(fw_transaction): use list.clear() in FirewallTransaction.clear()

list.clear() is functionally equivalent as del list[:]. However,
it seems less common and harder to read. It's also a bit slower
(on my python).
feat: add iperf{2,3} services

improvement(tests): automatically add the file name to AT_KEYWORDS()

Make it possible to select a test to run more explicitily.  For example,
many tests only have "rich" as keywords. So "-k rich" runs many tests.

Now, automatically also add various forms of the filename to
AT_KEYWORDS(). For example, the following now will all work:

  -k features/forward_ports.at:199
  -k features/forward_ports.at
  -k forward_ports.at:199
  -k forward_ports.at
  -k forward_ports
  -k features

improvement(fw-in-container): support running nftables test in container

fw-in-container is useful for testing and development.

Note that it runs a rootless container. For non-root users, the netlink
socket buffer is limited by /proc/sys/net/core/{rmem_max,wmem_max}. This
causes various tests inside fw-in-container to fail. The test also
cannot just bump that limit, because it's rootless (and because it would
be an undesirable modification of the host).

However, it's useful to support running such tests also inside the
container. All that we need, is that the user (as root) bumps those
host wide limits.

Extend the script to detect that, so that it can run.

If you now want to run those tests, first issue a

  echo 4096000 > /proc/sys/net/core/rmem_max
  echo 4096000 > /proc/sys/net/core/wmem_max
  echo 4096000 > /proc/sys/net/core/wmem_default

as root. You can get this simply by running:

  $ sudo ./contrib/fw-in-container/fw-in-container -S

chore(rich): simplify Rich_Limit and make hashable

Convert it to a frozen dataclass. This makes is simpler and also
hashable. If we expand this to the rest of the rich objects we can solve
some problems with rich rules:

- they're always normalized, e.g. `str(rich_obj)`
- can compare them directly rich_obj1 == rich_obj2
- no need to convert between objects and strings to determine existence
  - could instead do `if rich_obj in set_of_rich_objs`
  - also means we can use set operations, e.g. set1 + set2

I'd like to expand this approach to all rich rules objects.

improvement(rich): support "burst" attribute to limit in rich rules

For iptables, this is `-m limit --limit rate/suffix --limit-burst burst`.

For nftables, this is `limit rate [over] packet_number / TIME_UNIT [burst packet_number packets]`

Not implemented in `src/firewall-config.in`.

https://issues.redhat.com/browse/RHEL-9316

improvement(rich): add Rich_Limit.value_parse() and normalize value

Instead of duplicating the parsing, add a Rich_Limit.value_parse()
function that can be used to "understand" the value string.

Note that already previously, Rich_Limit.__init__() would normalize the
value (e.g. modify "/minute" to "/m"). Go one step further with this.
Now parse and stringify the value, so that it is normalized. Invalid
values are left unnormalized, and Rich_Limit.__init__() still does not
fail the operation (like before). For that we have check().

This normalization matters. For example, the parser is (rightfully)
graceful and will accept 'limit value="1 /m"'. If we add two rules
that are identical, except for the white space, we want that the
normalize string is identical. That's useful, because the normalized
string of a rule is used as identity for the rule.
